Supervised Learning - Foundations Project: ReCell¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Buying and selling used phones and tablets used to be something that happened on a handful of online marketplace sites. But the used and refurbished device market has grown considerably over the past decade, and a new IDC (International Data Corporation) forecast predicts that the used phone market would be worth \$52.7bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 13.6% from 2018 to 2023. This growth can be attributed to an uptick in demand for used phones and tablets that offer considerable savings compared with new models.

Refurbished and used devices continue to provide cost-effective alternatives to both consumers and businesses that are looking to save money when purchasing one. There are plenty of other benefits associated with the used device market. Used and refurbished devices can be sold with warranties and can also be insured with proof of purchase. Third-party vendors/platforms, such as Verizon, Amazon, etc., provide attractive offers to customers for refurbished devices. Maximizing the longevity of devices through second-hand trade also reduces their environmental impact and helps in recycling and reducing waste. The impact of the COVID-19 outbreak may further boost this segment as consumers cut back on discretionary spending and buy phones and tablets only for immediate needs.

Objective¶

The rising potential of this comparatively under-the-radar market fuels the need for an ML-based solution to develop a dynamic pricing strategy for used and refurbished devices. ReCell, a startup aiming to tap the potential in this market, has hired you as a data scientist. They want you to analyze the data provided and build a linear regression model to predict the price of a used phone/tablet and identify factors that significantly influence it.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of used/refurbished phones and tablets. The data was collected in the year 2021. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • brand_name: Name of manufacturing brand
  • os: OS on which the device runs
  • screen_size: Size of the screen in cm
  • 4g: Whether 4G is available or not
  • 5g: Whether 5G is available or not
  • main_camera_mp: Resolution of the rear camera in megapixels
  • selfie_camera_mp: Resolution of the front camera in megapixels
  • int_memory: Amount of internal memory (ROM) in GB
  • ram: Amount of RAM in GB
  • battery: Energy capacity of the device battery in mAh
  • weight: Weight of the device in grams
  • release_year: Year when the device model was released
  • days_used: Number of days the used/refurbished device has been used
  • normalized_new_price: Normalized price of a new device of the same model in euros
  • normalized_used_price: Normalized price of the used/refurbished device in euros

There are plenty of null values, however they are consistent with the brand name, year and operating system¶

As there is no specific column for the phone model, we can assume that phones with the same brand, year and OS are of the same model and that the null values are consistent with the model and not random. Due to this we can assume that phones with no mentioned Main Camera MP (which has the most null values) either do not have a back camera or the megapixels for those models were not listed¶

Section Summary:¶

  • There are 3454 rows and 15 columns
  • All the datatypes for each column seem appropriate and nothing needs to be converted
  • There are some null values, particularly significant for back camera MP
  • From filtering the dataset, we found the null values to be consistent with the phone's brand, OS and year
  • This indicates consistency between null values for specific phone models
  • To handle those, we must know if the specific models have/don't have a back camera
  • If they don't have a back camera, we can ignore the null values
  • If they have a back camera we can either look up the phone information for those models or if the data isn't available we can substitute the null value with the mean back camera megapixel value
  • There are no duplicate values
  • Refer to df.describe() for a direct statistical summary

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. What does the distribution of normalized used device prices look like?
  2. What percentage of the used device market is dominated by Android devices?
  3. The amount of RAM is important for the smooth functioning of a device. How does the amount of RAM vary with the brand?
  4. A large battery often increases a device's weight, making it feel uncomfortable in the hands. How does the weight vary for phones and tablets offering large batteries (more than 4500 mAh)?
  5. Bigger screens are desirable for entertainment purposes as they offer a better viewing experience. How many phones and tablets are available across different brands with a screen size larger than 6 inches?
  6. A lot of devices nowadays offer great selfie cameras, allowing us to capture our favorite moments with loved ones. What is the distribution of devices offering greater than 8MP selfie cameras across brands?
  7. Which attributes are highly correlated with the normalized price of a used device?

  • The attributes that are highly correlated with the used price are: 1) The price of the device when it was new 2) The screen size 3) The battery capacity 4) The resolution of the front and back cameras 5) The RAM

  • Surprisingly the internal memory has minimal correlation with the price of the device (even less so than the weight)

  • As expected, the number of days the device has been used has a negative correlation with the used selling price

In [52]:
# Filling null values with the median from each column
medianFiller = lambda x: x.fillna(x.median())
df_filled = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).apply(medianFiller, axis=0)

# Creating a copy of this dataset
df_copy_filled = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).apply(medianFiller, axis=0)

# Restoring non-numeric columns to the dataset
df_filled['brand_name']= df['brand_name'] 
df_filled['os']= df['os'] 
df_filled['4g']= df['4g'] 
df_filled['5g']= df['5g']

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

We need to check if the following assumptions hold:

  1. Linearity
  2. Independence
  3. Homoscedasticity
  4. Normality of error terms
  5. No strong Multicollinearity
  • In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.
  • We have already monitored and statistically proven that there is no strong Multicolinearity between our independent variables
In [42]:
df_pred = pd.DataFrame()

df_pred["Actual Values"] = y_train.values.flatten()  # actual values
df_pred["Fitted Values"] = olsres_6.fittedvalues.values  # predicted values
df_pred["Residuals"] = olsres_6.resid.values  # residuals

Test for Normality¶

  • Error terms/residuals should be normally distributed.
In [47]:
# Constructing a Histogram of Residuals

plt.title("Normality of residuals")
plt.show()
In [48]:
# Creating a Q-Q Plot 
import pylab
import scipy.stats as stats

stats.probplot(df_pred["Residuals"], dist="norm", plot=pylab)
plt.show()

Using the Shapiro-Wilk test to check for normality. The null and alternate hypotheses of the test are as follows:

  • Null hypothesis - Data is normally distributed.
  • Alternate hypothesis - Data is not normally distributed.
In [50]:
# Conducting the Shapiro-Wilk test
stats.shapiro(df_pred["Residuals"])
Out[50]:
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.9719365835189819, pvalue=2.305325709997579e-21)
  • While statistically, the test indicates that the data is not normally distributed, statistical tests are often highly scrutenizing and by referring to the plots above, we can see that most points follow a normal distribution, lying within the Q-Q line
  • Therefore we can still safely assume that our model's residuals follow a (relatively) normal distribution

Test for Homoscedasticity¶

  • If the variance of the residuals are symmetrically distributed across the regression line , then the data is said to homoscedastic.

  • We can test for homoscedasticity by using the goldfeldquandt test

The null and alternate hypotheses of the goldfeldquandt test are as follows:

  • Null hypothesis : Residuals are homoscedastic
  • Alternate hypothesis : Residuals have hetroscedasticity
In [99]:
import statsmodels.stats.api as sms
from statsmodels.compat import lzip
In [100]:
name = ["F statistic", "p-value"]
test = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(df_pred["Residuals"], X_train5)
lzip(name, test)
Out[100]:
[('F statistic', 1.060699691942269), ('p-value', 0.15371851296542877)]
  • Since p-value > 0.05 we can say that the residuals are homoscedastic.

Observations¶

  • R-squared and Adjusted R-squared of the model is 0.837, which shows that the model is able to explain ~84% variance in the data, which is satisfactory

  • A unit increase in the normalized new price will result in a 0.4312 unit increase in the normalized used price provided all other variables remaining constant.

  • The main camera resolution has a 44% greater influence on the price as compared to the selfie camera resolution

  • Other variables also contribute to the used price, specifically screen size (in cm) and release year whose unit increase accounts for 0.0428 and 0.0259 of the normalized used selling price respectively

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

The main predictors for the selling price of a used phone are:¶

  • The original asking price for the phone when it was new (the most significant predictor variable for selling price by far)
  • The screen size
  • Camera resolutions for both front and back facing cameras
  • The year in which the phone or tablet was released
  • Surprisingly, the brand of the phone/tablet or even the operating system had minimal correlation over the used selling price
  • The battery and weight of the phone also do not have much influence over the used selling price (however this can also be due to multicollinearity between battery capacity, weight and screen size)

Recommendations:¶

  • It is highly recommended to categorize whether the device is a phone or a tablet to better see which properties are more desirable in each device (eg. a larger screen size maybe more valuable for a tablet than a phone), this can lead to more accurate models and better insights on what influences the used selling price
  • Basing the used price mainly around the original sticker price is a sound estimation to make when initially pricing the phone
  • Focusing on refurbishing screens and cameras can be a good idea as the consumer puts more value on that than internal performance such as battery capacity and internal storage
